Hi Tomas,

It gives me a fast realtime view of what a thread is doing. Now you first
create the tread dump and inspect it afterwards.

A lot of times, I want to check the evolution of a single thread. Meaning, I
want to quickly inspect what it's doing now. 3 seconds later I want to
inspect it again f.e. to see if a blocking thread is still blocked. Then
check another thread f.e. to see why it's blocking the first one. A few
seconds later check that same thread again, etc...

To achieve the same result would require me to create a thread dump now.
Find the thread I'm looking for in TDA. Create another thread dump. Lookup
the same thread again to see if anything changed. Create another thread
dump. etc...

The application I'm currently working on, contains about 700 threads while
I'm often only interested in 1 or 2 of them. It just takes too long to
create a full thread dump of the entire application and inspect it later.
Jconsole however allows me to do inspect this in realtime.

I hope this makes sense to you.
Best regards
Jan



